📦 Inventory Management System (Java)

This project demonstrates an Inventory Management System implemented in Java using three important design patterns:

Singleton Pattern
Adapter Pattern
Iterator Pattern
🚀 Features
Maintain a centralized inventory using Singleton
Support both new products and legacy products
Integrate old system (LegacyItem) using Adapter
Traverse inventory using Iterator
🧠 Design Patterns Used
1. Singleton Pattern
Ensures only one instance of InventoryManager exists
Provides a global access point to inventory
2. Adapter Pattern
Converts LegacyItem into Product
Allows reuse of existing legacy code without modification
3. Iterator Pattern
Provides a standard way to traverse product collection
Uses Iterator interface (hasNext(), next())
🏗️ Project Structure
Inventory-Management-System/
│
├── Product.java
├── LegacyItem.java
├── ProductAdapter.java
├── NewProduct.java
├── InventoryManager.java
└── Main.java
💻 Technologies Used
Java
Core Java Collections (ArrayList, Iterator)
▶️ How to Run
1. Compile all files
javac *.java
2. Run the program
java Main
📌 Example Output
New Product -> Name: Laptop
New Product -> Name: Mobile
Legacy Item -> ID: 101, Description: Old Keyboard
Legacy Item -> ID: 102, Description: Old Monitor
📖 Class Description
🔹 Product (Interface)
Defines displayDetails() method
🔹 LegacyItem
Represents old system product
Uses print() method
🔹 ProductAdapter
Adapts LegacyItem to Product
🔹 NewProduct
Represents modern product structure
🔹 InventoryManager
Singleton class
Stores products in ArrayList
Provides iterator
🔹 Main
Entry point of the program
Demonstrates functionality
🎯 Learning Outcomes
Understanding of design patterns in real applications
Integration of legacy systems
Clean and modular object-oriented design
📌 Future Enhancements
Add GUI (JavaFX / Swing)
Add database integration (MySQL)
Implement search and delete operations
Add product categories and pricing

